the media in Canada. The authors focus on the context of media reports in Canada to show how claims about marijuana cultivation have intensified the perception that this activity poses “significant” dangers to public safety and thus is an appropriate target for Canada’s war on drugs.Boyd and Carter carefully show how the media draw on the same spokespeople to tell the same story again and again, and how a limited number of messages has led to an expanding anti-drug campaign that uses not only police, but BC Hydro and local municipalities to crack down on drug production. Going beyond the newspapers, Killer Weed examines how legal, political, and civil initiatives that have emerged from the media narrative have troubling consequences for a shrinking Canadian civil society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aDrug controlxHistoryxCanadax21st century. 0aDrug controlzCanaday21st centuryxHistory. 0aMarijuanaxGovernment policyxHistoryx21st centuryxCanada. 0aMarijuanaxGovernment policyzCanadaxHistoryy21st century. 0aMarijuanaxLaw and legislationxCanada. 0aMarijuanaxLaw and legislationzCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh1 aCarter, Connie , eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060681240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144269658740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442696587423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442696587.jpg  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles